00:05:05.080 --> 00:05:07.630
Multiple intelligences.

00:05:07.630 --> 00:05:09.420
Things that can be learned.

00:05:09.420 --> 00:05:11.550
There's a good "at play" project.

00:05:11.550 --> 00:05:16.130 position:59%
There's learning as a consequence of
thinking, and making learning visible.

00:05:16.130 --> 00:05:19.360
So, one thing to think about
that Project zero emphasizes is,

00:05:19.360 --> 00:05:20.860 position:58%
how do we know students are learning,

00:05:20.860 --> 00:05:27.340 position:63%
and what types of learning is much
relevant to our many different students.

00:05:27.340 --> 00:05:30.440
Specifically, Susan and I
look at artful thinking.

00:05:30.440 --> 00:05:34.910 position:56%
It's one of the several programs at
Project Zero, and what we're talking

00:05:34.910 --> 00:05:40.880 position:59%
about today is all linked by the theme
at artful thinking, visible thinking.

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:48.170 position:69%
One of the several projects visible thinking
has us look at the artful thinking pallet

00:05:48.170 --> 00:05:49.860 position:56%
with the many thinking dispositions.

00:05:49.860 --> 00:05:56.020 position:66%
We're going to share four of the six with
you, and talk about the different examples

00:05:56.020 --> 00:05:59.620 position:73%
that we use and activities that we use as well.

00:05:59.620 --> 00:06:04.910 position:73%
The goal of this artful thinking program is to
help the students develop thinking dispositions

00:06:04.910 --> 00:06:07.650 position:63%
that support, again thoughtful learning.

00:06:07.650 --> 00:06:13.600
So, let's move to the four that
we're going to talk about today.

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:14.780
Observe and describe.

00:06:14.780 --> 00:06:16.990
Question and investigate.

00:06:16.990 --> 00:06:18.960
Explore viewpoints.

00:06:18.960 --> 00:06:20.390
Compare and connect.

00:06:20.390 --> 00:06:26.790 position:64%
I want to note, too, that these visual
thinking dispositions are not necessarily

00:06:26.790 --> 00:06:30.090
in the hierarchy that they
look like in this list.

00:06:30.090 --> 00:06:33.730 position:64%
So, we're going to progress through these
in this order, but this does not need

00:06:33.730 --> 00:06:36.880 position:67%
to be strictly followed in your activities.

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:44.380 position:73%
The pallet is [inaudible] and it just as a
paint pallet, it provides you with many colors,

00:06:44.380 --> 00:06:49.620 position:75%
or in this case, thinking dispositions or
strategies that you can choose that are relevant

00:06:49.620 --> 00:06:52.910 position:58%
to your goals and to your objectives.

00:06:52.910 --> 00:06:55.560 position:66%
Okay, we're going to start with observing.

00:06:55.560 --> 00:06:58.880 position:73%
So, as we think about observing, it is sensing.

00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:04.420 position:56%
And, we want to start with observing
and not using words right away.

00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:08.440 position:66%
The ability to observe without evaluating.

00:07:08.440 --> 00:07:14.660 position:61%
Using observation without evaluating is
a really effective way to communicate.

00:07:14.660 --> 00:07:18.900
So, we work to encourage our
students to experience sense.

00:07:18.900 --> 00:07:24.200 position:63%
They can use their senses like seeing,
you can think about what you might hear,

00:07:24.200 --> 00:07:31.320 position:67%
what you might smell, what you might taste,
but experience this without the filters,

00:07:31.320 --> 00:07:35.970 position:63%
and subjective perception is emphasized.

00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:43.140
The next part of observe
and describe is describing.

00:07:43.140 --> 00:07:48.740 position:64%
So, this is where you're going to use
your words to represent what you observe.

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:55.000 position:66%
So, we can relate this to basic scientific
observation, making observations,

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:58.920 position:66%
of course, is a core skill of scientist's.

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:02.220
So, we receive the information,
again, through our senses.

00:08:02.220 --> 00:08:04.840 position:73%
When we think about the formal analysis of art,

00:08:04.840 --> 00:08:09.330
I ask my art students to
look at the elements of art.

00:08:09.330 --> 00:08:15.830 position:75%
So, when you describe, one thing to look for
which you're going to be doing in just a minute,

00:08:15.830 --> 00:08:17.490 position:56%
is to look for those seven elements.

00:08:17.490 --> 00:08:18.520
Look at the lines.

00:08:18.520 --> 00:08:19.730
Look at the shapes.

00:08:19.730 --> 00:08:25.720
Look at the forms, the space, the
color, the value, and the texture.

00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:28.370 position:69%
Also, of course, look at the subject matter.

00:08:28.370 --> 00:08:35.940 position:72%
You may see people, animals, landforms, things
that are man-made, things that are natural.

00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:43.840
Now, this is where we want
you to start observing.

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:49.970 position:58%
We have provided an image, and in
this image, take a minute to observe.

00:08:49.970 --> 00:08:56.830
Use your sense of sight, and
think about what you see.

00:08:56.830 --> 00:09:03.690 position:56%
We'd like for you to share your
thoughts and type your observations.

00:09:03.690 --> 00:09:10.750 position:58%
So, you can start describing what you
see in this visual representation.

00:09:10.750 --> 00:09:12.560
Make note of the features.

00:09:12.560 --> 00:09:14.100
Look at the subject matter.

00:09:14.100 --> 00:09:16.020
Look at the elements of art.

00:09:16.020 --> 00:09:18.860
I see smoke.

00:09:18.860 --> 00:09:22.270 position:56%
Paul sees that they're sharing food.

00:09:22.270 --> 00:09:25.620
&gt;&gt; Or, burning eyes, that's
a good one [laughter].

00:09:25.620 --> 00:09:26.950
&gt;&gt; Terry sees bread.

00:09:26.950 --> 00:09:30.290
Bridgett sees an ocean.

00:09:30.290 --> 00:09:31.660
Great observations.

00:09:31.660 --> 00:09:32.900
Keep describing.

00:09:32.900 --> 00:09:35.190
Keep looking.

00:09:35.190 --> 00:09:38.440
The act of sharing, Jennifer's.

00:09:38.440 --> 00:09:41.030
Lee sees Native people sitting.

00:09:41.030 --> 00:09:46.320 position:72%
Oh, Paul indicates that some are well-dressed.

00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:48.220
Ada sees a man with a gun.

00:09:48.220 --> 00:09:52.900 position:70%
I like the Liam counted eight men, two women.

00:09:52.900 --> 00:09:56.900 position:69%
Oh, Paul's already getting to the questions.

00:09:56.900 --> 00:10:00.390 position:61%
Is there a Minister in the black, left?

00:10:00.390 --> 00:10:06.990 position:63%
One thing that I focused on when I asked
my students to observe and to describe

00:10:06.990 --> 00:10:12.310 position:58%
which is very difficult for us to do,
is to not jump to in [inaudible] yet,

00:10:12.310 --> 00:10:19.150
to really just observe and describe
what you see in the picture.

00:10:19.150 --> 00:10:20.850
A man with a beard.

00:10:20.850 --> 00:10:21.740
Lots of hands.

00:10:21.740 --> 00:10:28.420 position:64%
So, I'm going to ask you to think about
some questions as you continue to observe

00:10:28.420 --> 00:10:32.080 position:72%
and describe, and read each other's responses.

00:10:32.080 --> 00:10:36.170 position:59%
Did you observe and describe features?

00:10:36.170 --> 00:10:39.500 position:66%
Did you observe and describe similarities?

00:10:39.500 --> 00:10:41.250
And, differences?

00:10:41.250 --> 00:10:45.580 position:75%
Did you observe and describe the subject matter?

00:10:45.580 --> 00:10:48.850 position:70%
Also, are you looking at the elements of art?

00:10:48.850 --> 00:10:52.820
Are you looking at the lines,
and the colors, and the shapes?

00:10:52.820 --> 00:10:57.280 position:56%
I see Samantha is already looking at
a variety of colors in the clothing.

00:10:57.280 --> 00:11:03.520 position:56%
Of course, having an image that's
not online makes that easier to see.

00:11:03.520 --> 00:11:09.510 position:75%
These are just some of the questions that I just
posed as you were participating, and still are,

00:11:09.510 --> 00:11:12.490 position:56%
in this first level of the activity.

00:11:12.490 --> 00:11:19.650 position:69%
&gt;&gt; I think it's very hard too, when you have
some background knowledge about an image not

00:11:19.650 --> 00:11:24.650
to launch past describing and go
right in to deferring, inferring,

00:11:24.650 --> 00:11:27.470
and so I think that that's a
difficult thing for us to do,

00:11:27.470 --> 00:11:29.690 position:64%
and sometimes for students to do as well.

00:11:29.690 --> 00:11:31.540
&gt;&gt; Absolutely.

00:11:31.540 --> 00:11:37.040 position:61%
So, some variations of this activity as
you continue to observe and describe,

00:11:37.040 --> 00:11:38.980 position:56%
I'm having so much fun reading this.

00:11:38.980 --> 00:11:41.610
Sarah, I like your question;
Is she handing out pancakes?

00:11:41.610 --> 00:11:48.370 position:66%
But, some variations include; filtering or
focusing on a specific part of the image.

00:11:48.370 --> 00:11:53.290
So, very often Susan and
I will start with one part

00:11:53.290 --> 00:11:56.970 position:69%
of the image and not share the entire image.

00:11:56.970 --> 00:12:02.800 position:67%
And, for, especially for our young students
that makes it not so overwhelming to see

00:12:02.800 --> 00:12:06.760
so much visually, and they
can just focus on a part.

00:12:06.760 --> 00:12:10.870 position:58%
They can also look at the whole thing
and then we can focus on the parts.

00:12:10.870 --> 00:12:14.970
So, we can part to whole, or
whole to part with this strategy.

00:12:14.970 --> 00:12:19.860 position:56%
So, you can begin with that very
zoomed in part, and ask the learners

00:12:19.860 --> 00:12:29.450 position:75%
to visually describe what they see, and then
you can add more visual information to the task.

00:12:29.450 --> 00:12:36.020 position:70%
This elaboration game requires you to ask
one student to describe what they see in part

00:12:36.020 --> 00:12:39.860 position:69%
of the image, and then progress to the next.

00:12:39.860 --> 00:12:45.110 position:70%
Additionally, the game can help student's use
more sophisticated descriptive vocabulary,

00:12:45.110 --> 00:12:47.020 position:61%
because they're building on each other.

00:12:47.020 --> 00:12:53.540 position:69%
The collaboration and the building on ideas
increases that community, and that teamwork,

00:12:53.540 --> 00:12:57.240 position:66%
and it models the power of a group effort.

00:12:57.240 --> 00:13:02.960 position:75%
&gt;&gt; I don't know why, but when I do this
activity I really like going from part to whole,

00:13:02.960 --> 00:13:08.880 position:64%
and reviewing a little bit at a time,
and then having the students actually add

00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:13.270
to their observations as we widen.

00:13:13.270 --> 00:13:17.650
&gt;&gt; These are some pictures from a
classroom, and this is another way

00:13:17.650 --> 00:13:22.760 position:69%
that I facilitate this strategy of observing
and describing in the art classroom.

00:13:22.760 --> 00:13:25.350
I use a set of laminated
posters that I've collected

00:13:25.350 --> 00:13:28.710 position:64%
over the years, and we use post-it notes.

00:13:28.710 --> 00:13:33.780
I equip my students with a
pen and a stack of post-its.

00:13:33.780 --> 00:13:40.750 position:66%
I display about 10 to 30 posters of
various works of art, sometimes on tables,

00:13:40.750 --> 00:13:45.360 position:72%
sometimes we display them on the walls, and
the students are instructed to think of a word

00:13:45.360 --> 00:13:49.210
or a phrase to describe and
stick to each poster.

00:13:49.210 --> 00:13:54.060
They must respond to each work
of art without duplication.

00:13:54.060 --> 00:13:57.000 position:66%
So, they cannot duplicate their own words,

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:00.480
or the words of their classmates
that are already on the posters.

00:14:00.480 --> 00:14:03.720
They walk around, and they're
allowed to talk if they talk

00:14:03.720 --> 00:14:07.600
about their perceptions and
descriptions of the artwork.

00:14:07.600 --> 00:14:12.990 position:67%
This always generates many conversations,
and initial reactions to a number of works,

00:14:12.990 --> 00:14:15.360 position:58%
usually which are new to my students.

00:14:15.360 --> 00:14:22.140 position:70%
It includes vocabulary, they share their
multiple perceptions, and their descriptions.

00:14:22.140 --> 00:14:27.710 position:56%
Susan and I have even done this at a
visual literacy workshop with people

00:14:27.710 --> 00:14:30.790
from all over the world in Ireland.

00:14:30.790 --> 00:14:37.090 position:64%
And, these are just some more ideas about
the describe it, post-it activity that is

00:14:37.090 --> 00:14:44.160 position:63%
so successful with students and having
them look and just observe and describe.

00:14:44.160 --> 00:14:50.620 position:67%
As you'll see in artful thinking at Project
Zero, very similar activities like colors,

00:14:50.620 --> 00:14:54.560
lines, shapes, and looking at the
elements of art are advocated.

00:14:54.560 --> 00:15:01.590 position:70%
Looking 10 by two process is a great process
